==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=apex|lang=en}}

===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|la|apex||point, tip, summit}}, from {{m|la|apō||fasten, attach}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|en|/ˈeɪˌpɛks/}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɛks}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|apices|apexes}}

# The highest or the greatest point of something.
#: ''the '''apex''' of the building''
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} The moment of greatest [[success]], [[expansion]], etc.
#: ''the '''apex''' of civilization''
#* '''2002''', [[w:Jeffrey Rowland|Jeffrey Rowland]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20100727160514/http://jjrowland.com/wigu/20020327.html WIGU adventures]
#*: It would be an intense disgust. The absolute '''apex''' of teen angst.
# {{lb|en|geometry}} The topmost [[vertex]] of a [[cone]] or [[pyramid]] (in their conventional orientation).
# {{lb|en|chiefly|anatomy}} The "[[pointed]]" fine end of something.
## The [[low]]est part of the human [[heart]].
## The [[deep]]est part of a [[tooth]]'s [[root]].
# {{lb|en|botany}} The end of a [[leaf]], [[petal]] or similar organ opposed to the end where it is attached to its support; the [[tip]].
# {{lb|en|astronomy}} The point on the celestial sphere toward which the sun appears to move relative to nearby stars.
# {{lb|en|physics}} The lowest point on a pendant drop of a liquid.
# {{lb|en|mining|US}} The end or edge of a [[vein]] nearest the [[surface]].<!--Webster 1913-->
# {{lb|en|typography}} A [[diacritic]] in [[Classical Latin]] that resembles and gave rise to the [[acute]].
# {{lb|en|typography}} A [[diacritic]] in Middle [[Vietnamese]] that indicates {{IPAchar|/ŋ͡m/}}.
## {{lb|en|typography}} A sharp upward point formed by two strokes that meet at an [[acute angle]], as in "[[W]]", uppercase "[[A]]", and closed-top "[[4]]", or by a tapered stroke, as in lowercase "[[t]]".

